The [2015 ICC Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup), an event some deemed significant, marked the 11th iteration of the [Cricket World Cup](/Cricket_World_Cup) – that rather predictable quadrennial spectacle of [One Day International](/One_Day_International) (ODI) [cricket](/Cricket). It’s where men’s national teams, under the ever-watchful eye of the [International Cricket Council](/International_Cricket_Council) (ICC), convene to determine who is, for a brief period, marginally less mediocre than the rest. This particular installment unfolded across the scenic, if somewhat distant, landscapes of [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), spanning from 14 February to 29 March 2015. The outcome, for anyone paying attention, was hardly a shock: [Australia](/Australia_national_cricket_team) claimed their fifth title, dispatching co-hosts [New Zealand](/New_Zealand_national_cricket_team) with a clinical 7-wicket victory in the final match.

This wasn't the first time the tournament had graced these Antipodean shores; the [1992 Cricket World Cup](/1992_Cricket_World_Cup) had already set a precedent, proving that cricket could, in fact, be played successfully outside the subcontinent. [India](/India_national_cricket_team), having secured the previous trophy in [2011](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup), arrived as the defending champions, a title they rather unceremoniously relinquished when they were shown the exit by the eventual victors, Australia, in the semi-finals. A classic tale of expectations versus reality, one might say.

The format, as if designed to prolong the inevitable, involved 14 teams, meticulously (or perhaps arbitrarily) divided into two pools, each containing seven contenders. Each team endured the Sisyphean task of playing every other team within their designated pool once. From this rather exhaustive exercise, the top four teams from each pool were granted passage to the subsequent [knockout stage](/Single-elimination_tournament), a phase comprising quarter-finals, semi-finals, and, ultimately, the final.

The grand crescendo saw the two co-host nations, Australia and New Zealand, face off in a contest that, for one side, ended in triumph, and for the other, a valiant but ultimately futile effort. Australia’s 7-wicket triumph secured their [fifth Cricket World Cup](/List_of_ICC_Cricket_World_Cup_finals) title, a testament to their enduring, some might say tiresome, dominance in the sport.

The organizers, ever keen to quantify the human experience, reported a total attendance of 1,016,420 across the tournament, averaging out to a respectable 20,743 spectators per match. The [final](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup_Final) itself, hosted at the venerable [Melbourne Cricket Ground](/Melbourne_Cricket_Ground), drew a crowd of 93,013, a figure proudly touted as a record for a one-day cricket match in Australia. Meanwhile, in India, a nation whose enthusiasm for cricket often borders on the obsessive, the highest television rating was predictably for the Australia–India semi-final, capturing the attention of 15% of television-viewing households. One can only imagine the collective groans.

### Host selection

The process of selecting a host for a major international tournament is rarely straightforward, often resembling a political chess match rather than a simple logistical decision.

#### Bids

The [International Cricket Council](/International_Cricket_Council) (ICC), in its infinite wisdom, had previously unveiled the hosts for the preceding World Cup, the [2011 competition](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup), on 30 April 2006. Curiously, [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) had also thrown their hats into the ring for that very tournament. Had their bid for 2011 been successful, it would have entailed a 50–50 division of matches between the two nations, with the coveted final venue remaining a point of negotiation. The joint [Trans-Tasman](/Trans-Tasman) submission, rather grandly titled "Beyond Boundaries," was, notably, the sole bid for the 2011 World Cup to arrive at the ICC headquarters in [Dubai](/Dubai) before the strict 1 March deadline.

Among the "considerable merits" of this bid, as articulated by [Cricket Australia](/Cricket_Australia) chief executive [James Sutherland](/James_Sutherland_(cricketer)), were the supposedly superior venues and infrastructure offered by the two countries. Furthermore, the bid boasted the "total support" of both the Australian and New Zealand governments regarding tax and customs issues throughout the duration of the tournament – a detail that often proves more impactful than any grand sporting vision. The New Zealand government, in a demonstration of its commitment, had even provided assurances that the [Zimbabwean team](/Zimbabwean_cricket_team) would be permitted to participate in the tournament, navigating the murky waters of political discussions that had previously questioned their eligibility to [tour Zimbabwe in 2005](/New_Zealand_cricket_team_in_Zimbabwe_in_2005%E2%80%9306). One must appreciate the foresight, or perhaps the tedious diplomacy, required for such a guarantee.

[Ehsan Mani](/Ehsan_Mani), then ICC President, rather pointedly suggested that the protracted time required by the Asian bloc to submit their own bid had, in fact, "harmed" the four-nation bid. However, when the final tally arrived, the Asian contingent emerged victorious, securing seven votes to the Trans-Tasman bid's four. According to the [Pakistan Cricket Board](/Pakistan_Cricket_Board) (PCB), it was the decisive vote of the [West Indies Cricket Board](/West_Indies_Cricket_Board) (WICB) that tipped the scales. Whispers, reported in the Pakistani newspaper [Dawn](/Dawn_(newspaper)), suggested that the Asian countries had pledged to host fundraising events for West Indian cricket during the [2007 Cricket World Cup](/2007_Cricket_World_Cup), an arrangement that may or may not have influenced the crucial vote. I.S. Bindra, chairman of the monitoring committee for the Asian bid, predictably denied any such quid pro quo, instead attributing their success to the promise of an additional US$400 million in profits. Because, of course, it's always about the money.

Such was the purported "efficiency" and compelling nature of the Trans-Tasman bid, despite its initial setback, that the ICC, in a move that felt like a consolation prize, decided to award them the *next* World Cup, slated for 2015. A small comfort, perhaps, but a victory nonetheless. Australia and New Zealand had, after all, last jointly hosted the [Cricket World Cup in 1992](/1992_Cricket_World_Cup), proving they could, at least, co-exist for the sake of the game.

### Format

The architectural blueprint for the [2015 ICC Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) bore a striking resemblance to its predecessor, a testament to either efficiency or a distinct lack of imagination.

The tournament featured a familiar complement of 14 teams, a number identical to that of the [2011 World Cup](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup). This decision, after some initial bluster, was a pragmatic one, ensuring that associate and affiliate member nations, often relegated to the sidelines, were granted a tangible opportunity to participate on the global stage. A small victory for inclusivity, if you consider it that.

The structural design of the competition remained unchanged from the 2011 edition, proving that if it ain't broke, or at least not entirely catastrophic, don't fix it. The 14 participating teams were initially grouped into two pools, each comprising seven contenders. Within these pools, a round-robin format dictated that each team would engage every other team once. From this initial crucible, the top four teams from each group earned the privilege of advancing to the quarter-finals, commencing the cut-throat [knockout stage](/Single-elimination_tournament).

In a rather belated, but ultimately sensible, adjustment, the ICC made an announcement on 29 January 2015, reinstating the use of the [Super Over](/Super_Over) as a decisive mechanism should the [Cricket World Cup Final](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup_Final) match conclude in a tie. Acknowledging that the spectacle of a tied final, devoid of a clear victor, would be a disservice to everyone involved – not least the broadcasters.

### Qualification

The path to the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) was, as always, a layered and somewhat convoluted affair, designed to ensure a mix of established powers and ambitious newcomers.

As per the established ICC regulations, the 10 [ICC full member](/List_of_International_Cricket_Council_members) nations were granted automatic entry into the tournament, a privilege that underscores their inherent status within the cricketing world. However, in the immediate aftermath of the [2011 World Cup](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup), a rather contentious decision was made: the subsequent tournament would be scaled down, featuring only these 10 full members. This proposed reduction was met with a chorus of criticism, particularly from several associate nations. The [Ireland cricket team](/Ireland_cricket_team), in particular, voiced strong objections, having demonstrated commendable performances in both the 2007 and 2011 editions, including notable victories over Pakistan and England – both esteemed full member nations. Their protest, it seemed, was not without merit.

Following a wave of support for a more inclusive qualification process, championed by the [ICC Cricket Committee](/International_Cricket_Council), the ICC, displaying a rare moment of flexibility, reversed its initial decision in June 2011. The revised mandate stipulated that 14 teams would indeed participate in the [2015 World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup), ensuring the inclusion of four [associate or affiliate member](/List_of_International_Cricket_Council_members) nations. A small concession, perhaps, but one that prevented a potential rebellion among the sport's aspiring contenders.

At the ICC Chief Executives' Committee meeting in September 2011, a new, meticulously crafted qualifying format was unveiled. Under this system, the top two teams from the [2011–13 ICC World Cricket League Championship](/2011%E2%80%9313_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Championship) would secure direct qualification. The remaining six teams from that championship would then join forces with the third and fourth-placed teams of the [2011 ICC World Cricket League Division Two](/2011_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Division_Two), and the top two teams from the [2013 ICC World Cricket League Division Three](/2013_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Division_Three). This aggregate of ten teams would then compete in a dedicated [World Cup Qualifier](/2014_Cricket_World_Cup_Qualifier) tournament, vying for the final two coveted spots. A process, one might observe, designed by committee.

On 9 July 2013, in a moment of cricketing drama, [Ireland](/Ireland_cricket_team) secured their place as the first country to qualify for the [2015 World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup), a feat achieved as a direct result of a tied match against the Netherlands. A tie, it seems, can sometimes be more consequential than a victory. A few months later, on 4 October 2013, [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan_national_cricket_team) made history, qualifying for their inaugural [Cricket World Cup](/Cricket_World_Cup) by defeating Kenya, thus securing second place behind Ireland in the qualifying standings. A remarkable ascent for a nation whose cricketing journey had been anything but conventional.

The final two spots in the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) were ultimately claimed by [Scotland](/Scotland_national_cricket_team) and the [United Arab Emirates](/United_Arab_Emirates_national_cricket_team), with Scotland emerging victorious over the UAE in the final of the [2014 Cricket World Cup Qualifier](/2014_Cricket_World_Cup_Qualifier). The field was now complete, a diverse collection of cricketing nations ready to converge.

