                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Cricket World Cup is a quadrennial [One Day International](/One_Day_International) (ODI) [cricket](/Cricket) tournament. It is organized by the sport's global governing body, the [International Cricket Council](/International_Cricket_Council) (ICC), and is contested by men's national teams. The 2015 edition was jointly hosted by [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) from 14 February to 29 March 2015.

The tournament culminated in [Australia](/Australia_national_cricket_team) securing their fifth title, defeating their co-hosts [New Zealand](/New_Zealand_national_cricket_team) by a margin of 7 wickets in the final. This marked the second instance of the tournament being held in Australia and New Zealand, with the first being the [1992 Cricket World Cup](/1992_Cricket_World_Cup). [India](/India_national_cricket_team), the champions of the preceding edition in [2011](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup), were eliminated in the semi-finals by the eventual champions, Australia.

The competition featured 14 teams, which were divided into two pools of seven. Each team played every other team within its respective pool once. The top four teams from each pool then advanced to the [knockout stage](/Single-elimination_tournament), which comprised quarter-finals, semi-finals, and the final.

The final match, a trans-Tasman showdown, was contested between the co-hosts Australia and New Zealand. Australia emerged victorious by seven wickets, thus claiming their [fifth Cricket World Cup](/List_of_ICC_Cricket_World_Cup_finals) title.

The tournament attracted a total attendance of 1,016,420 spectators, yielding an average of 20,743 attendees per match. The [final](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup_Final) at the [Melbourne Cricket Ground](/Melbourne_Cricket_Ground) notably drew a crowd of 93,013, setting a new record for a one-day cricket match in Australia. In India, the semi-final clash between Australia and India garnered the highest television rating, reaching 15% of television-viewing households.

### Host selection

The selection of host nations for the [Cricket World Cup](/Cricket_World_Cup) is a process often fraught with political maneuvering and competitive bidding, a testament to the significant prestige and economic benefits associated with staging such a global event.

#### Bids

The [International Cricket Council](/International_Cricket_Council) (ICC) had previously announced the hosts for the preceding World Cup, the [2011 competition](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup), on 30 April 2006. Interestingly, [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) had also submitted a joint bid for the 2011 tournament. A successful Australian bid for the 2011 World Cup would have resulted in a 50–50 split in the allocation of matches between the two nations, with the venue for the final remaining a subject for negotiation.

The [Trans-Tasman](/Trans-Tasman) bid, ambitiously titled "Beyond Boundaries," was the sole submission for the 2011 World Cup to reach the ICC headquarters in [Dubai](/Dubai) before the stringent 1 March deadline. The bid highlighted "considerable merits," as articulated by [Cricket Australia](/Cricket_Australia) chief executive [James Sutherland](/James_Sutherland_(cricketer)), including their purportedly superior venues and infrastructure. Furthermore, it underscored the comprehensive support from both the Australian and New Zealand governments concerning tax and customs issues for the duration of the tournament, a crucial element for any large-scale international event. The New Zealand government had also provided assurances that the [Zimbabwean team](/Zimbabwean_cricket_team) would be permitted to participate in the tournament, navigating prior political discussions regarding whether their team would be allowed to [tour Zimbabwe in 2005](/New_Zealand_cricket_team_in_Zimbabwe_in_2005%E2%80%9306). These governmental guarantees often speak louder than any sporting promise.

[Ehsan Mani](/Ehsan_Mani), the then-ICC President, observed that the extended time taken by the Asian bloc to submit its bid had inadvertently "harmed" the four-nation bid. However, when the votes were ultimately cast, the Asian consortium triumphed by a margin of seven votes to four. According to the [Pakistan Cricket Board](/Pakistan_Cricket_Board) (PCB), it was the vote of the [West Indies Cricket Board](/West_Indies_Cricket_Board) (WICB) that proved decisive. Reports in the Pakistani newspaper [Dawn](/Dawn_(newspaper)) suggested that the Asian countries had pledged to organize fundraising events for West Indian cricket during the [2007 Cricket World Cup](/2007_Cricket_World_Cup), a gesture that may have influenced the outcome of the vote. Conversely, I.S. Bindra, chairman of the monitoring committee of the Asian bid, vehemently denied any such influence, asserting that their promise of an additional US$400 million in profits was the true factor that swayed the vote in their favour. It seems the allure of financial gain often trumps other considerations.

Despite the loss for the 2011 bid, the ICC was reportedly "so impressed" by the detailed and efficient nature of the Trans-Tasman submission that they subsequently decided to award the *next* World Cup, scheduled for 2015, to Australia and New Zealand. A clear demonstration that persistence, and a well-structured proposal, can eventually pay off. Australia and New Zealand had previously shared hosting duties for the [Cricket World Cup in 1992](/1992_Cricket_World_Cup), making this a return to a familiar and successful partnership.

### Format

The structural design of the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) largely mirrored that of its immediate predecessor, indicating a preference for established frameworks over radical innovation.

The tournament was planned to feature 14 teams, maintaining the same number as the [2011 World Cup](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup). This continuity was significant, as it ensured that associate and affiliate member nations continued to have a pathway to participate in the prestigious global event, a decision that wasn't always a given in ICC deliberations.

The format itself was a direct replication of the 2011 edition. The 14 participating teams were initially divided into two distinct groups, each comprising seven teams. Within these groups, a comprehensive round-robin stage was conducted, where every team competed against all other teams in their pool once. Following this initial phase, the top four teams from each group earned their progression to the [knockout stage](/Single-elimination_tournament). This subsequent phase was structured in a classic single-elimination bracket, featuring quarter-finals, semi-finals, and culminating in the final match.

In a crucial and widely welcomed decision, the ICC announced on 29 January 2015, just ahead of the tournament, the reinstatement of the [Super Over](/Super_Over) for the [Cricket World Cup Final](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup_Final) match should it conclude as a tie. This move effectively ensured that the ultimate championship match would always yield a definitive winner, preventing the anticlimactic scenario of sharing the trophy or relying on other tie-breaking criteria that had been debated in the past.

### Qualification

The road to the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) was a dynamic process, reflecting the ongoing debates within the [International Cricket Council](/International_Cricket_Council) (ICC) regarding inclusivity and the balance between established cricketing nations and emerging ones.

According to the standing ICC regulations, the 10 [ICC full member](/List_of_International_Cricket_Council_members) nations were granted automatic qualification for the tournament, a standard practice acknowledging their historical contribution and current standing in the sport. However, a significant controversy arose immediately after the conclusion of the [2011 World Cup](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup), when the ICC initially decided that the subsequent tournament would be reduced to feature only these 10 full members. This proposal was met with vehement criticism from a multitude of associate nations, most notably from the [Ireland cricket team](/Ireland_cricket_team). Ireland had consistently demonstrated their capability on the world stage, achieving impressive results in both the 2007 and 2011 tournaments, including notable victories over full member nations like Pakistan and England. Their performance, it was argued, clearly justified their continued participation.

Responding to this considerable backlash and following strong advocacy from the ICC Cricket Committee for a more robust qualification process, the ICC reversed its controversial decision in June 2011. This pivotal change meant that 14 teams would indeed participate in the [2015 World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup), ensuring the inclusion of four [associate or affiliate member](/List_of_International_Cricket_Council_members) nations, thus providing a vital pathway for emerging cricketing talent.

At the ICC Chief Executives' Committee meeting in September 2011, a refined and detailed qualifying format was officially adopted. Under this structure, the top two teams from the [2011–13 ICC World Cricket League Championship](/2011%E2%80%9313_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Championship) earned direct qualification to the World Cup. The remaining six teams from that championship then proceeded to a 10-team [World Cup Qualifier](/2014_Cricket_World_Cup_Qualifier). This qualifier also included the third and fourth-placed teams from the [2011 ICC World Cricket League Division Two](/2011_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Division_Two), and the top two teams from the [2013 ICC World Cricket League Division Three](/2013_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Division_Three). This multi-tiered system was designed to determine the final two places in the World Cup.

The qualification journey saw its first success on 9 July 2013, when [Ireland](/Ireland_cricket_team) secured their spot for the [2015 World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) following a tied match against the Netherlands, a result that proved sufficient for their standing. Shortly thereafter, on 4 October 2013, [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan_national_cricket_team) made a historic entry, qualifying for their first-ever [Cricket World Cup](/Cricket_World_Cup) by defeating Kenya, thereby finishing in second place behind Ireland in the [WCL Championship](/2011%E2%80%9313_ICC_World_Cricket_League_Championship).

The final two coveted spots were claimed by [Scotland](/Scotland_national_cricket_team) and the [United Arab Emirates](/United_Arab_Emirates_national_cricket_team), both of whom emerged from the [2014 Cricket World Cup Qualifier](/2014_Cricket_World_Cup_Qualifier). Scotland ultimately defeated the United Arab Emirates in the final match of that qualifier, ensuring both teams' participation in the 2015 global showpiece.

