### Preparations

The meticulous orchestration required for a global sporting event like the [Cricket World Cup](/Cricket_World_Cup) necessitates extensive preparation, from establishing leadership to logistical arrangements and visa policies.

#### Local organising committee

In anticipation of the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup), the formation of the local organising committee was a critical initial step, ensuring that the complex task of staging the tournament was entrusted to a dedicated leadership team. [John Harnden](/John_Harnden) was appointed as the chief executive, tasked with overseeing the operational aspects and day-to-day management of the event. [James Strong](/James_Strong_(cricketer)) assumed the role of chairman, providing strategic direction and leadership to the committee. Complementing this leadership, [Ralph Waters](/Ralph_Waters) was named as the deputy chairman. However, the committee faced an unexpected challenge with the unfortunate passing of James Strong in March 2013, necessitating a shift in leadership. Following this event, Ralph Waters stepped up to assume the position of chairman, ensuring continuity in the tournament's preparatory phase.

#### Allocation of matches

The distribution of matches between the co-host nations was a significant point of negotiation, especially given the shared responsibility. When [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) initially bid for the [2011 Cricket World Cup](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup) back in 2006, their proposal had envisioned an equitable 50–50 split of the games. Ultimately, a definitive decision was reached on 30 July 2013, stipulating that Australia would host 26 matches, while New Zealand would be allocated 23 matches throughout the tournament.

A particularly "tense battle," as it was described, unfolded between the major Australian cities of [Melbourne](/Melbourne) and [Sydney](/Sydney) for the prestigious right to host the final match. The culmination of this rivalry was announced on 30 July 2013, confirming that the [Melbourne Cricket Ground](/Melbourne_Cricket_Ground) would host the final. Meanwhile, the semi-final matches were allocated to Sydney and [Auckland](/Auckland), ensuring that key knockout fixtures were distributed across both host nations.

#### Visas

To facilitate easier access for international spectators attending the World Cup matches, a special arrangement was put in place. It was announced that spectators travelling to World Cup matches in [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) who would not ordinarily be eligible for a visa waiver would be permitted to enter New Zealand if they possessed a valid Australian visitor visa. This was officially termed the "special Trans-Tasman Visa Arrangement for the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup)." This pragmatic measure aimed to streamline travel logistics and enhance the fan experience across both host countries.

### Media and promotion

The [Cricket World Cup](/Cricket_World_Cup), like any major global sporting event, relies heavily on media exposure and strategic promotion to capture public imagination and secure its financial viability. This particular section, however, comes with a rather telling caveat, suggesting it "may rely excessively on sources too closely associated with the subject," potentially compromising its verifiability and neutrality. A polite way of saying: take it with a grain of salt.

It's been observed that the World Cup has "grown as a media event with each tournament." A statement so self-evident it almost doesn't need saying. The [International Cricket Council](/International_Cricket_Council) (ICC), ever astute to the commercial value, secured a substantial deal, selling the broadcasting rights for the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) for an astounding US$2 billion to [ESPN Star Sports](/ESPN_Star_Sports) and [Star Sports](/Fox_Sports_(Southeast_Asian_TV_network)). This figure alone speaks volumes about the perceived global reach and market value of the tournament.

According to James Strong, the then-chairman of the Local Organising Committee (LOC), the ambition was to position the tournament as the "most fan-friendly event of its kind" and to "take cricket to a wide range of communities throughout Australia and New Zealand." A noble sentiment, one might suppose, though the definition of "fan-friendly" can often be subjective.

The ICC, recognizing the enduring appeal of cricketing legends, appointed [Sachin Tendulkar](/Sachin_Tendulkar) as the World Cup Ambassador for the second consecutive time, a role he had previously fulfilled for the [2011 Cricket World Cup](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup). His presence undoubtedly lent an air of gravitas and widespread recognition to the promotional efforts.

The sheer demand for certain matches was evident in ticket sales. Reports indicated that tickets for the highly anticipated [India v Pakistan](/India%E2%80%93Pakistan_cricket_rivalry) clash in [Adelaide](/Adelaide) were snapped up within a mere 12 minutes of going on sale – a testament to the fervent rivalry and massive fan bases of both nations. This particular match also commanded a significant television audience in India, registering an average of 14.8% of TV-equipped households. The semi-final between Australia and India subsequently achieved an even higher average rating in India, reaching 15.0%. However, despite these impressive figures, no single match in the 2015 tournament managed to surpass the viewership numbers achieved by the [2011 Final](/2011_Cricket_World_Cup_Final) among Indian viewers, a subtle indicator that even in a cricket-mad nation, peaks are hard to sustain. The 2015 World Cup, in fact, took place against a backdrop of reported "declining viewing figures for cricket in India," a trend that prompted some introspection within the industry. Despite this, broadcaster Star Sports proudly asserted that its coverage of the tournament reached an astonishing 635 million viewers in India. An ICC-commissioned report, perhaps with a touch of hyperbole, even claimed that the tournament was watched by "over 1.5 billion people" globally. These numbers, while impressive, are often subject to various methodologies and interpretations, and should perhaps be viewed with a critical eye.

