### Knockout stage

The [knockout stage](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup_knockout_stage) of the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) represented the sharp end of the competition, where single-elimination matches determined which teams would advance and which would face the ignominy of going home. While the dates and venues for these crucial matches were pre-determined, a pragmatic flexibility was built into the schedule: the specific match-ups could be adjusted to accommodate the host countries, [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), should they qualify.

Both host nations, as expected, successfully progressed to the quarter-finals. Australia played their quarter-final match on 20 March in [Adelaide](/Adelaide), while New Zealand hosted their quarter-final on 21 March in [Wellington](/Wellington). Following this, [Sri Lanka](/Sri_Lanka_national_cricket_team), being the next highest [ranked team](/ICC_ODI_Championship) to qualify, was slated to play their quarter-final in [Sydney](/Sydney). Had [England](/England_cricket_team) advanced, as the third-highest ranked team from the group stage, they would have played in [Melbourne](/Melbourne). However, England’s rather underwhelming performance meant they failed to qualify for the quarter-finals, and their spot was subsequently taken by [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh_national_cricket_team). The pairings for the quarter-finals were structured logically, following the sequence of A1 vs B4, A2 vs B3, A3 vs B2, and A4 vs B1.

New Zealand’s semi-final encounter against [South Africa](/South_Africa_national_cricket_team) was played on 24 March in [Auckland](/Auckland), setting the stage for a tense trans-Tasman rivalry. Australia’s semi-final clash with [India](/India_national_cricket_team) took place on 26 March in [Sydney](/Sydney). In a fitting, if somewhat predictable, turn of events, both host nations ultimately qualified for the final. The tournament culminated with [Australia](/Australia_national_cricket_team) emerging victorious, defeating [New Zealand](/New_Zealand_national_cricket_team) by 7 wickets to claim the trophy.

