### Controversies

No major sporting event is truly complete without its share of contentious moments, and the [2015 Cricket World Cup](/2015_Cricket_World_Cup) was no exception. These incidents, often fueled by split-second decisions and intense nationalistic fervor, inevitably sparked debate and, in some cases, outright outrage.

*   The Pool A match between [Australia](/Australia_national_cricket_team) and [England](/England_cricket_team) concluded amidst a flurry of confusion when [James Anderson](/James_Anderson_(cricketer)) was controversially run out immediately after [James Taylor](/James_Taylor_(cricketer,_born_1990)) had been given out [lbw](/Leg_before_wicket). The critical detail emerged later: Taylor's decision was reviewed and subsequently overturned. The ICC, in a rare admission of fallibility, later conceded that the ball *should* have been declared [dead](/Dead_ball_(cricket)) (as per Article 3.6a of Appendix 6 of the Decision Review System Playing Conditions). This meant, unequivocally, that Anderson's dismissal was incorrect. A clear demonstration of how human error, even with the aid of technology, can still manage to muck things up.

*   During the Pool B match featuring [Ireland](/Ireland_cricket_team) and [Zimbabwe](/Zimbabwe_national_cricket_team), a pivotal moment occurred during a tight run chase. [Sean Williams](/Sean_Williams_(cricketer)) was caught by Ireland's [John Mooney](/John_Mooney_(cricketer)), but the legality of the catch was immediately questioned. Mooney was positioned precariously close to the boundary rope, and a staggering eight different television replays proved utterly inconclusive as to whether his foot had made contact with the boundary. Despite this ambiguity, Williams, perhaps resigned to his fate or simply adhering to the spirit of the game, [walked](/Glossary_of_cricket_terms) off, and the umpires signaled him out. A decision made in the fog of war, where definitive proof remained elusive.

*   The second quarter-final match, a heated clash between [India](/India_national_cricket_team) and [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh_national_cricket_team), became a veritable hotbed of controversy, sparking diplomatic incidents and accusations of bias. One particular flashpoint involved [Rubel Hossain](/Rubel_Hossain) bowling a [full toss](/Full_toss) to [Rohit Sharma](/Rohit_Sharma), who was subsequently caught at square-leg. However, the umpire deemed the ball to be excessively high and declared it a [no-ball](/No-ball), thereby nullifying the dismissal and allowing Sharma to continue batting. This decision, to put it mildly, did not go down well with the Bangladeshi camp. Furthermore, there was another instance involving [Shikhar Dhawan](/Shikhar_Dhawan) catching a ball hit by [Mahmudullah Riyad](/Mahmudullah_Riyad) near the boundary line, with accusations surfacing that Dhawan's leg had touched the boundary rope *after* completing the catch, though replays again offered no conclusive evidence.

    The fallout was swift and dramatic. The ICC's own Bangladeshi President, [Mustafa Kamal](/Mustafa_Kamal), publicly questioned the integrity of the umpire's decision and went so far as to threaten to resign in protest. Not to be outdone, Bangladesh's Prime Minister, [Sheikh Hasina](/Sheikh_Hasina), weighed in, unequivocally stating that India had won the match solely due to "umpiring errors." This, of course, presented the ICC with a rather inconvenient public relations nightmare. ICC chief executive [Dave Richardson](/Dave_Richardson_(South_African_cricketer)) was forced to respond, dismissing the accusations as "baseless" and founded on the "personal feelings of an individual." He asserted that the no-ball incident was a "50–50 call" and that the ultimate decision rested squarely with the umpire. A classic case of post-match recrimination, where the outcome of a game transcends mere sport to become a matter of national pride and perceived injustice.

